    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Expanding NATO</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ken Whelan expresses doubts about United States foreign policy plan to incorporate Balkans into Europe and expand NATO to the Black Sea (Robert D Kaplan's Oct 6 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Yugoslavia's Fate, and Europe's,'' by Robert D. Kaplan (Op-Ed, Oct. 6):</p>
        <p>A United States foreign policy to incorporate the Balkans into Europe and expand NATO to the Black Sea is a big stretch that suggests considerable arrogance by ''American authority.'' And what does it mean to say that the Balkans ''are a natural area for our expansion''? Imperialism by proxy?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Yugoslavia's Fate, and Europe's,'' by Robert D. Kaplan (Op-Ed, Oct. 6):</p>
        <p>A United States foreign policy to incorporate the Balkans into Europe and expand NATO to the Black Sea is a big stretch that suggests considerable arrogance by ''American authority.'' And what does it mean to say that the Balkans ''are a natural area for our expansion''? Imperialism by proxy?</p>
        <p>NATO has plenty on its plate, and the European Union needs to digest what it has eaten. To be sure, other powers in the area will have a say as to the future of the Balkans, including the Balkans themselves.</p>
        <p>KEN WHELAN  San Francisco, Oct. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
